Step-by-step reasoning:

1. Key psychological mechanisms:
   • Participants use the observed (sample‐based) expected rewards (from forced and prior free choices) to guide which option pays better.
   • In addition to pure exploitation (reward maximization), there is an explorative drive: options sampled less during the forced-choice phase have higher uncertainty and may be appealing (a “novelty” or “information bonus”). Moreover, participants tend to explore more when more free choices are available (long horizon).

2. Interaction of mechanisms:
   • The utility of an option is determined by a linear combination of its exploitation value (its observed expected reward) and an exploration bonus that rewards less-observed (i.e. more “informative”) options.
   • The overall decision utility also may include a fixed bias term and an additive effect for long-horizon (horizon = 6) games.

3. Mathematical form to capture interactions:
   • For a free-choice trial, we compute a “relative utility” for choosing option 1 over option 0. This will be a weighted sum of the difference in expected rewards and the difference in forced-sample counts (with the sign chosen so that the option with fewer forced plays gets a bonus). An additive bias term and a horizon modifier are also added.

4. Learnable parameters needed:
   • beta0: an intercept (bias) parameter.
   • beta_exploit: sensitivity to the difference in expected rewards.
   • beta_explore: sensitivity to the difference in forced-sample counts (information bonus), applied with a minus sign so that fewer forced samples (i.e. less known) yield higher utility.
   • beta_horizon: a bonus that is added in long-horizon (6 free-choice) games.
   Finite bounds are provided for all learnable parameters.

5. Mapping to observable behavior:
   • The model uses the observed expected_reward0 and expected_reward1 (from previous plays) along with information on the number of forced-choice plays available for each option (computed from the forced_choice indicator, where for each game the first four trials provide counts per option).
   • These combine linearly to yield a utility value (U). This utility is later passed through a logistic function to yield a probability for binary (0 vs. 1) free choices. The model is set up to predict UTILITY (the linear combination) rather than the probability.

Below is the formal model specification.

––––––––––––––––––––––
<MODEL>
U = beta0 + beta_exploit*(expected_reward1 - expected_reward0) - beta_explore*((forced_count1) - (forced_count0)) + beta_horizon*I(horizon == 6)
</MODEL>

